		<tooltip id="tt_24">
			<description>This are &quot;special locations&quot; defined by the application's <html:b>OS.Constants.Path</html:b> module. This are somewhat equivalent to the system's environment variables. Instead of using a full path to a location, you can use one of this <em>constants</em>. The menu to the right is auto-generated and pre-filled with all the <em>constants</em> that your application supports.</description>
		</tooltip>
		<tooltip id="tt_25">
			<description>This field allows you to modify the path generated by the <html:b>Constant</html:b> field. A value in this field of 1, for example, will remove from the <html:b>Constant</html:b> path one director (goes up one directory).</description>
		</tooltip>
		<tooltip id="tt_26">
			<description>Final part of a path in relation to the path generated by the <html:b>Constant</html:b> field (after being modified by the <html:b>Go up</html:b> field).</description>
			<description class="bold_text">Notes:</description>
			<html:ul>
				<html:li>Forward slashes or backslashes can be used for defining a path in this field. It doesn't matter the platform, this field is platform agnostic. You could use backslashes for Linux paths and/or forward slashes for Windows paths.</html:li>
				<html:li>This field has to have at least one slash.</html:li>
				<html:li>Do not mix forward slashes with backslashes in the same path. Choose one or the other.</html:li>
				<html:li>Backslashes doesn't need to be escaped. Multi Menu takes care of that.</html:li>
			</html:ul>
		</tooltip>
		<tooltip id="tt_27">
			<description>If <html:b>enabled/checked</html:b>, the URL for this item will be opened regardless if that exact URL is already opened in another tab. If <html:b>disabled/unchecked</html:b>, and the URL for this item is already opened in another tab, instead of opening a new tab, it will switch to the first tab found containing that exact URL.</description>
		</tooltip>
		<tooltip id="tt_z1">
			<description>A <html:b>Custom menu item</html:b> can execute any code defined by the user.</description>
		</tooltip>
		<tooltip id="tt_z2">
			<description>A <html:b>Custom menu</html:b> can contain any type of item.</description>
		</tooltip>
		<tooltip id="tt_z3">
			<description>A <html:b>Cloned menu item</html:b> is a cloned version of an existent menu item.</description>
			<description><html:b>Note:</html:b></description>
			<description>Only items with defined IDs can be cloned.</description>
		</tooltip>
		<tooltip id="tt_z4">
