<body>
	<h2>About this GUI (Graphical User Interface)</h2>
	<h3>General usage</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>All items inserted from the <b>Insert a new item</b> menu are appended at the end of the main menu from the current selected tab.</li>
		<li>Items can be re-ordered and/or moved into any <em>menugroup</em> element or <em>custom menu</em> at any level by just dragging them while pressing the <b>%A_C_C_E_L%</b> key.</li>
		<li>Items can be moved into any other main popup (tab) from the context menu.</li>
		<li>While having opened any edit dialog on the currently selected main menu/tab, it isn't possible to switch to other main menus/tabs. Changes on the currently selected main menu/tab will have to be saved or canceled to be able to work on other main menus/tabs.</li>
		<li>Every time the <b>Save changes</b> button is pressed, and before the main items file is modified with the new changes, a backup of the current items file is created. So, returning to a previous functional items file is as easy as to renaming the last backup file.</li>
		<li>A maximum of three backup files are created and available at all times.</li>
		<li>Orange colored fields are <span class="bold_text required" >REQUIRED</span></li>
		<li>Green colored fields are <span class="bold_text optional">OPTIONAL</span></li>
		<li>Red colored fields are <span class="bold_text experimental">EXPERIMENTAL</span></li>
	</ul>
	<p>
	<div class="important-notes">
		<h3>Important notes</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Menugroup elements and custom menu elements <b>MUST NOT</b> be placed inside another menugroup 	elements. If you do, and then save the changes, you will loose all menugroup/menu children if any.</li>
			<li>In all elements with custom command fields, the global object (<b>this</b>) is the button to which the menu/menu item belongs. So be very careful NOT to override properties of the global object. Additionally, all variables/objects that are available on the execution context of any button, like <b>self</b>, <b>Cc</b>, <b>Ci</b>, etc., are also available on the execution context of the code defined on these fields.</li>
			<li>If you edit the items file manually (with any text editor), know that its content is in JSON format. Which means that its syntax is very strict. A single misplaced comma could completely break the menu. So, you must use a proper text editor with a JSON linter to edit this file. Otherwise, stick to edit the items with this GUI.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
</body>
</html><!--%HelpPage%-->

